after slider. **Aha:** URL \u2192 score + instant rewrites. **Why it matters:** 70%+ of sites fail basic accessibility; devs feel this guilt personally.\n\n**4. Syllabus Sprint** \u2014 *Education*\nUpload a syllabus PDF, get a spaced-repetition study calendar mapped to your exam dates, exportable to Google Calendar/.ics. **Aha:** syllabus \u2192 week-by-week plan rendered on a real calendar UI. **Why it matters:** every student, every semester, same problem.\n\n**5. Explain Back** \u2014 *Education* *(risky/novel)*\nYou explain a concept in your own words; it maps precisely where your mental model breaks, highlighting the exact sentence where your understanding diverges \u2014 Feynman technique, automated. **Aha:** your paragraph \u2192 \"you went wrong *here*\" annotations. **Why it matters:** flips the AI-explains-to-you paradigm; nobody else is building this.\n\n**6. Standup Story** \u2014 *Work and Productivity*\nPaste your raw `git log`; get a polished standup update in three tones (manager, team, client). **Aha:** cryptic commits \u2192 human narrative. Trivially buildable, but thin impact ceiling. **Why it matters:** daily pain for every developer alive.\n\n**7. PR Review Map** \u2014 *Developer Tools*\nPaste a public GitHub PR URL; get a risk-ordered review plan \u2014 files grouped by danger, suggested review sequence, time estimate. **Aha:** PR link \u2192 color-coded review map. **Why it matters:** review fatigue is real, but AI-code-review is a crowded lane.\n\n**8. Paper to Practice** \u2014 *Education*\nSnap a photo of any textbook problem; get an interactive step-through quiz that checks each step of your work. **Aha:** photo \u2192 playable quiz. **Why it matters:** converts passive reading into active recall; risk is generation variance eating your polish time.\n\n**9. Fridge Triage** \u2014 *Apps for Your Life*\nPhoto of your fridge interior \u2192 three recipes ranked by which ingredients expire soonest. **Aha:** photo \u2192 recipe cards with \"use by Friday\" tags. **Why it matters:** food waste is a $400B problem, but the recipe-from-photo space is saturated.\n\n**10. Tab Triage** \u2014 *Work and Productivity*\nPaste your open-tab list; get clusters, a \"close these 30\" verdict, and a one-page digest of what each tab was for. **Aha:** 80 tabs \u2192 \"keep 9.\" **Why it matters:** universally relatable, low stakes \u2014 a fun demo, a weak moat.\n\n---\n\n**Verdict: #1 Fine Print Flag.** It dominates the median submission on all four axes: legible 30-second aha (upload \u2192 risk card), a massive real audience (impact), a genuinely complete product when scoped to one document type (design), and a clean Codex showcase (PDF parsing + structured clause extraction). #2 Thread Decider is the differentiated backup if you want to leverage your CatchUp story.\n\n\nWhat unstated assumptions do these ideas share? Which assumptions, if wrong, would invalidate the most promising ideas?\n\nAnalyst A: ### Final Assessment of Hackathon Assumptions\n\n#### 1. Valid Assumptions\n*   **Judges score the demo, not the code:** In a 3-day hackathon, evaluation is heavily narrative- and vibe-driven. A flawlessly choreographed 30-second video demo showcasing a pre-curated happy path is highly effective, rende...\nAnalyst B: [Model unavailable: codex - codex exec failed (rc=1): Reading additional input from stdin...\nNot inside a trusted directory and --skip-git-repo-check was not specified.\n]\nAnalyst C: ## Final Assessment \u2014 Analyst C\n\n### 1. Valid Assumptions (survived scrutiny)\n\n- **C2 \u2014 Judges score the scripted demo.** Analyst A's cross-exam holds: 2\u20133 minute judging windows reward legible narrative, and nobody stress-tests edge cases. Trust it as a strategy anchor \u2014 but only with a non-broken ...",
